messages.author: sky
messages.text:
The style guide says classes like this should be in their owner header: "Prefer putting delegate classes in their own header files. Implementors of the delegate interface will often be included elsewhere, which will often cause more coupling with the header of the main class."

Also, add a virtual destructor in the protected section.

messages.author: sky
messages.text: Does this need to be virtual?

messages.author: sreeram
messages.text:
On 2012/12/03 22:22:23, sky wrote:
> The style guide says classes like this should be in their owner header: "Prefer
> putting delegate classes in their own header files. Implementors of the delegate
> interface will often be included elsewhere, which will often cause more coupling
> with the header of the main class."

Right. However, all the implementors of this interface include instant_client.h anyway (because they each have an "InstantClient client_;" object member). So I didn't see the value in separating this out. Let me know if you still feel strongly.

> Also, add a virtual destructor in the protected section.

Done.

messages.author: sreeram
messages.text:
On 2012/12/03 22:22:23, sky wrote:
> Does this need to be virtual?

No. But without it, the clang style plugin or some such gives an error saying that "all classes that override a virtual method must have a virtual destructor" (and this class does have a couple of OVERRIDE declarations).

On 2012/11/29 19:57:05, Jered wrote:
> Should this check full_text.empty() as it used to?

No, user_text is the right thing here. If we are in case #2, full_text won't be empty, but user_text will be, and match_is_search will be true. We don't want to create a loader in that case.

Previously, full_text worked because case #2 never triggered (i.e., recall the changes in this CL to use view_->GetText() instead of user_text + inline_autocomplete_text_ in omnibox_edit_model.cc).

messages.text:
On 2012/12/03 19:46:03, samarth wrote:
> Yikes! The last two clauses appear all over the place--worth making utilities
> for them for clarity? For example, IsLoaderActive() and IsTabActive()? (There's
> probably better names you could use here.)

Actually, it's just in two places - the only two callbacks that are applicable to both InstantTab and InstantLoader, viz., SetSuggestions() and InstantSupportDetermined(). Until this proliferates, I think it's simpler to just keep them as they are.

The other similar checks, such as the ones in Update(), are conceptually different. They are not checking whether instant_tab_ or loader_ match the caller's contents; rather that the instant_tab_ contents match the active tab contents. I think it might lead to more confusion if we tried to share code across them.

messages.author: sreeram
messages.text:
On 2012/11/29 19:57:05, Jered wrote:
> Wow, I hope not. Do we not want to update the blacklist in this case?

No. The blacklist is to make sure that we are not causing unnecessary and repeated page loads. In the case of a committed tab, we are not actually causing any loads. We are just using what's already there. No resources wasted, so no need to blacklist.

messages.author: sreeram

> Is this CreateDefaultLoader() call new? I think this is safe because of
> blacklisted_urls_, but initially I was worried this might result in an infinite
> loop of creating and deleting the default loader... that can't happen, right?

Yeah, the call is new. The infinite loop can't happen because of kMaxInstantSupportFailures, but this code will eventually be overhauled when http://crbug.com/143722 is fixed. So, I'll keep this change for now.
